UDP (User Datagram Protocol)
Overview

UDP (User Datagram Protocol) is a protocol used to communicate data between devices.

It sends data using datagrams.

Unlike TCP, UDP does not establish a constant connection between devices.

No three-way handshake occurs in UDP.



General Characteristics

There is no synchronization between devices before sending data.

UDP is used where some data loss is acceptable.



Common use cases:

Video streaming

Voice chat

Useful when connection stability is not critical.



Advantages of UDP

UDP is faster than TCP.

The application (user software) decides how quickly packets are sent.

No continuous connection is maintained between devices.



Disadvantages of UDP

UDP does not verify whether data is received or not.

No acknowledgement mechanism.

Unstable connections can lead to poor user experience.

There are no safeguards like TCP to ensure data integrity.



Characteristics of UDP Packets

UDP packets are simpler than TCP packets.

They contain fewer headers compared to TCP.

Some standard headers are still included.



UDP Packet Headers


Time To Live (TTL)

Sets an expiration timer for the packet.

Prevents packets from circulating in the network forever.


Source Address

The IP address of the sending device.

Helps data know where it originated from.


Destination Address

The IP address of the receiving device.

Tells the data where it should be delivered.

Ports in UDP Communication


Source Port

Port opened by the sender to send the UDP packet.

Usually randomly chosen from available ports.

Range: 0 – 65535.


Destination Port

Port number of the application/service on the receiving host.

Example:

Web server runs on port 80.

Not chosen randomly.


Data Field

Contains the actual transmitted data.

Example: bytes of a file or message.



UDP Communication

No connection setup occurs before communication.

No acknowledgement is sent during communication.
